reviews.review: Best way to close a saga... I loved the movie, every part of this movie put me on different stages, tons of emotions, I laughed, I cried, I felt the sadness and the joy, there were a lot of crossed feelings for sure, but at the end took me were everything started and I felt the peace in my heart wondered what's next... for now I suggest patience masters and we'll see... May the force be with you all...

Terrible movie. Pacing is off, the emotional notes are largely unearned. It answers long-standing questions unsatisfyingly, and then brings up new unsatisfying questions which it never bothers to answer. There are a couple of good action scenes, in a couple of really cool Concepts, but overall the plot is lazy. If I didn't know better I would think that JJ Abrams had never written a script before.

Is better than The Last Jedi, but that's a very low bar. At least it tries to undo what Rian Johnson did. No political agenda non-sense add a point for sure.
It has some very good scenes, to be honest, and the main characters at least share some screen time together.

This was quite a unique way to send off this massive spectical of an epic saga. It was an absolute blast to witness the end of such profound characters of old and new. Can't wait for more exciting things to come for our beloved franchise. May the Force Be with us üëãüèª

I give it a 6.5/10
The story was decent overall, the first act rushed through different locations presumably to try to cover a lot of the plotholes of The Last Jedi. Second act was good, a few weird decisions and a couple blatant plotholes. Third act started to look amazing, but then was completely undermined by the ending. The ending not only contradicted the previous films but contradicted itself moments before.

It tried to do the opposite of everything I hated from The Last Jedi, which was not focusing on old characters and plots, Rise Of Skywalker tried to connect the Original Trilogy and the prequels with the movie, and I loved that.
Star Wars!  Do I need to say anything further...
The editing made it feel like a 2hr trailer. How many recuts do you have to do to achieve that?
